      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Fast Bureaucracy</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Greek bureaucracy moves slowly. Build extra time into your plans. What takes days elsewhere may take weeks in Greece.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Island Internet Expectations</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Small islands have limited, inconsistent internet. Test thoroughly before committing. Athens and major islands are fine.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing Tax Registration</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">To claim the 50% tax reduction, you must register with Greek tax authorities and get an AFM number. Don't skip this step.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Island Healthcare Limitations</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Small islands have basic clinics only. Serious issues require boat/helicopter to Athens. Ensure evacuation coverage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Summer-Only Planning</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Many islands shut down in winter. If planning year-round, choose Athens, Thessaloniki, or larger islands like Crete.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Dependent Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Income threshold increases with dependents: +20% for spouse, +15% per child. Calculate correctly before applying.</p>
      </div>
